    // Education
    education_title: 'Understanding Your Training Numbers',
    education_content: '**Your Current Status**\n\nFitness (CTL): {ctl}\nFatigue (ATL): {atl}\nForm (TSB): {tsb}\nRecovery: {recovery}\n\nResting HR: {rhr} \u00b7 HRV: {hrv} \u00b7 Sleep: {sleep}\nWeekly load change: {weekly_change}\n\n**Lactate Threshold \u2014 Your Engine\'s RPM Limit**\n\nThink of your body as a car engine.\nAt low RPMs everything runs smoothly.\nPush harder \u2192 the engine heats up.\nPast a certain RPM \u2192 overheating.\n\nThat RPM is your **lactate threshold**.\n\nBelow threshold \u2192 body clears lactic acid as fast as it builds.\nAbove threshold \u2192 acid accumulates. You "redline".\n\n**TRIMP \u2014 "How Many Bags of Sand Did I Move"**\n\nLight day \u2192 3 bags.\nHard day \u2192 20 bags.\nRace \u2192 50+ bags.\n\nTRIMP = duration \u00d7 HR intensity.\nThe total physical toll of your session.\nYour latest TRIMP: {trimp}\n\n**hrTSS \u2014 Same Thing, Normalized**\n\nLike TRIMP, but 1 hour at threshold = exactly 100.\nEasier to compare across athletes and disciplines.\nYour latest hrTSS: {hrtss}\n\n**CTL \u2014 "How Fit Am I"**\n\n42-day weighted average of daily TRIMP.\nYour CTL: {ctl}\nHigher = more training your body can handle.\n\n**ATL \u2014 "How Tired Am I Right Now"**\n\n7-day average of daily TRIMP.\nYour ATL: {atl}\nRises fast after hard training, drops fast with rest.\n\n**TSB \u2014 "Am I Ready to Perform?"**\n\nTSB = CTL \u2212 ATL = {tsb}\n\n[dot:#c3e88d] Positive = fresh and ready to race\n[dot:#ffc777] Near zero = balanced training\n[dot:#ff966c] Slightly negative = building fitness\n[dot:#ff5370] Very negative = fatigued, need recovery\n\nRace day target: +10 to +25.\n\n**Practical Rules**\n\n**1. The 10% Rule**\nNever increase weekly load by more than 10%.\nYour current change: {weekly_change}\n\n**2. The 3:1 Rule**\n3 weeks progressive load \u2192 1 week recovery (reduce 40\u201350%).\nThe safest way to build fitness.\n\n**3. The Savings Account**\nFitness = savings account.\nTraining = deposits. Recovery = withdrawals.\nOverspend \u2192 bankruptcy (injury, burnout).',
