    detail_cardiac_drift: 'Cardiac Drift Analysis',
    detail_cardiac_drift_info: '**Cardiac Drift**\nHow much HR rises in the 2nd half vs 1st half at similar pace.\nReveals aerobic efficiency and fatigue resistance.\n\n**Thresholds**\n< 5% = Excellent aerobic base\n5-8% = Moderate — approaching aerobic ceiling\n> 8% = Pace too aggressive, or dehydration/overheating\n\nLower drift over time = improving fitness.',
    info_cadence: '**Cadence** (steps/min)\nNumber of steps per minute.\n\n**Good range**\n170-180 spm = optimal for distance running\n160-170 = common in easy runs\n180+ = elite or speed work\n\nHigher cadence reduces impact per step and injury risk.',
    info_gct: '**Ground Contact Time** (ms)\nHow long each foot stays on the ground per step.\n\n**Good range**\n200-250 ms = fast, efficient running\n250-300 ms = recreational pace\n300+ ms = slow, heavy landing\n\nLower GCT at same pace = better running economy.',
    info_stride: '**Stride Length** (m)\nDistance covered per step.\n\n**Good range**\n1.0-1.2 m = typical at easy pace\n1.2-1.5 m = tempo/race pace\n1.5+ m = sprinting\n\nOverstriding (too long) increases braking force and injury risk.',
    info_power_run: '**Running Power** (W)\nEstimated total effort including horizontal + vertical movement.\n\n**Good range**\n180-220 W = easy pace\n220-280 W = tempo\n280-350 W = threshold/intervals\n\nPower/pace ratio reveals running efficiency.',
    info_power_bike: '**Cycling Power** (W)\nDirect force measurement at the pedals.\n\n**Reference**\nZ1 Recovery: < 55% FTP\nZ2 Endurance: 56-75% FTP\nZ3 Tempo: 76-90% FTP\nZ4 Threshold: 91-105% FTP\nZ5 VO2max: 106-120% FTP',
    info_cadence_bike: '**Cycling Cadence** (rpm)\nPedal revolutions per minute.\n\n**Good range**\n80-95 rpm = optimal for endurance\n70-80 = grinding (more muscular)\n95-110 = spinning (more cardiovascular)\n\nConsistent cadence improves efficiency.',
    info_swolf: '**SWOLF Score**\nSwim efficiency = time (sec) + strokes per 25m length.\n\n**Good range (25m pool)**\n30-40 = competitive swimmer\n40-50 = good recreational\n50-60 = beginner\n\nLower = more efficient. Track over time to measure improvement.',
    info_swolf_100: '**SWOLF Score (per 100m)**\nSWOLF = time (sec) + strokes per 100m.\n\n**Good range (25m pool)**\n120-160 = competitive swimmer\n160-200 = good recreational\n200-240 = beginner\n\nLower = more efficient. Comparable across 100m segments.',
    info_strokes: '**Strokes per 25m**\nNumber of arm pulls per pool length.\n\n**Good range (freestyle 25m)**\n12-16 = efficient technique\n16-20 = average\n20+ = short, choppy strokes\n\nFewer strokes at same pace = better technique.',
    info_strokes_100: '**Strokes per 100m**\nTotal arm pulls per 100m (strokes/25m × 4).\n\n**Good range (freestyle)**\n48-64 = efficient technique\n64-80 = average\n80+ = short, choppy strokes\n\nCompare across sets to spot fatigue — stroke count rising = form breaking down.',
